text: hi everyone please the new vote tano
here the internet's busiest music nerd
and it's time for a review of the new
spillage
village album spiligen this is the
sophomore full-length lp
of georgia-based rap collective spillage
village
with input from black deontay hitchcock
earth gang jid among others
spillage currently boasts some of the
most young exciting talent
in hip-hop's left field right now this
new lp also comes at just the right time
because multiple members are fresh off
of well-received projects and features
now a few of the teasers leading up to
this thing sounded pretty good but given
how large of a collective spillage
village is
i didn't assume every track was going to
sound like end of days and baptized
i was pretty excited to see how the deep
cuts on this thing would play out but
what ended up grabbing my attention is
just how
far spillage tries to stretch the
themes of religion and spirituality
throughout this thing
from the cover looking like a weird take
on some extravagant christian mural
there's a somewhat preachy introduction
skit to
kick the entire project off too then
through the rest of the tracks we have
heavy references
to jesus god baptisms
psalms prayer mecca and various bits of
christian mythology
but it's all wrapped in subtly
psychedelic production eccentric rapping
and lots of group
singing too in a way it sort of sounds
like a combo of the underachievers
outcast gospel music but all that being
delivered by a band of hip-hop hippies
enjoying their vacation at christian
summer camp
there's a decent amount of diversity
among the beats on this thing too
like the dub reggae influenced effects
rhythms and bass lines on mecca the
acoustic guitar is an uplifting group of
vocals on song sing
the smooth low-key funky trap of ocean
and let's also not forget the punchy yet
smooth jazz rap of shiva so with
attention grabbing names
consistent themes and versatility
spillage village has everything you
would want out of a collective
on paper but in practice this project
feels like it's missing something a lot
of the time
for one there are some pretty obvious
gaps in mic time talent and presence
between all the members and features
like the jordan bryant verse at the
finish of end of days which is kind of
stiff and sticks out for all the wrong
reasons
much of the time it's jid and earth gang
leading the pack on this thing vocally
and lyrically
though i'm not entirely sure how well
they complement each other here there's
already so much overlap
in terms of vocal style in earth gang
throwing jid into the mix doesn't
exactly help the issue
especially since lyrically he's not
bringing the same
level of heat that he was on dicaprio 2
for example
a lot of the time considering how many
verses he has on this project it should
be
and yet it's not and not to single him
out because i don't think he's the only
person on this project who's not going
the extra mile
which i think is evidenced in the fact
that the more i get hit with religious
references on this thing
the more apparent it becomes that this
whole spirituality narrative
feels more like an aesthetic than it is
a genuine concept
because it's rare that jids or johnny's
or
dot's lyrics come off as deeply pious or
anything like that
still i do enjoy many of the sentiments
on this record around peace
love family equality but the
spirituality that anchors it all down
comes off like window dressing meant to
simply make the music sound more
mystical or otherworldly keep in mind
i'm not making a commentary here on the
religious beliefs of any one person on
this record
i'm just saying as far as the music goes
it's not exactly a religious experience
especially during the album's weakest
moments there is
judas which features a very rough
interpolation of hit the road jack
and obnoxious chanceverse a beat that is
so off-kilter it's hard to really
get a grip of it then around the
midpoint there's a lot of vocals a lot
of
singing pig piling on top of each other
but nothing's really taking a strong
lead
there is some sing that i mentioned
earlier which does have some great and
respectable group vocals
but the moment marib's verses hit the
foreground the track
instantaneously turns mild there is
ocean which has a
painfully sleepy verse from black right
at the kickoff though i can't just
simply single him out on this song
because every verse on it is utterly
forgettable
meanwhile cupid is an awkward attempt at
a musical flirt with these messy
out-of-tune vocal harmonies and chunky
rhythms johnny's wild first verse is the
only thing about the track content-wise
that struck
me as remotely memorable and there were
even some parts of it that made me kind
of wince

they're not

baptize end of days most likely you guys
have heard these tracks going into this
review
and while i do enjoy both of them are
they the best
songs i've ever heard jid or earth gang
attach themselves to
not necessarily plus both of them
feature these unnecessarily
drug out endings that don't really add
that much to the song in my opinion
then we also have this very sweet and
tuneful family cut with
jid singing on the hook quite nicely
sparkling acoustic guitars heavenly
group
vocals the whole thing sounds like an
idyllic slice of life celebrating love
family togetherness weed smoking too
because why not the incredibly inspiring
verse from hollywood jb on the back end
is really the
stand out for me then we also have the
inspired and
multi-phased hoppy the church bells the
pianos the colorful singing
the vocal switch-offs there's a lot
going on here there's something so raw
and beautiful about it and i like the
unlikely structure to it all too
there's mariba's low-key spot on the
first leg
then this spotlit stunning pastoral
sung verse from johnny it sounds like a
transmission
from god then we have a few verses to
end things off with an instrumental
switch
a few more verses to end things off one
of which is from atlanta legend big rube
very moving thought-provoking and poetic
way to end the track off
and also top off the album a little bit
in a way i think rube
ties up a lot of the themes and meaning
of the record better than some of the
core members of spillage village have
then there's a really quaint acoustic
outro with more group singing which i
think
is another one of the characteristics of
spillage that kind of makes them stand
out makes them special but overall
the record itself um a little
indifferent toward it
certainly there's potential here in the
future but
i don't know i just left this thing
wanting more a lot more
stronger songs topical focus more
consistent performances
and if religion is going to play a
pivotal role in the narrative of
spillage's
sound and music i would love a deeper
embrace
of the themes that are inspiring that
rather than this endless stream of
surface level references
feeling a strong five to a light six on
this one
